\b\fs28 Step 2 - Generate Schedule in R\
\

\b0\fs24 If this is not the first schedule you\'92ve generated, move the previous \'93schedule.xlsx\'94 and \'93employeeHours.xlsx\'94 files out of the \'93Scheduler\'94 folder.\
\
Open up the R Application, copy and paste the following chunk of code into the console (after the \'93>\'94), and press enter/return:\
\

\f1\fs22 setwd('~/Desktop/Scheduler')\
source('~/Desktop/Scheduler/generateSchedule.R')\
generateSchedule()
\f2\fs24 \
\

\f0 Two files: \'93schedule.xlsx\'94 and \'93employeeHours.xlsx\'94 should have appeared in the Scheduler folder.\
\'93schedule.xlsx\'94 is the actual schedule that will be pasted into the format template\
\'93employeeHours.xlsx\'94 is a file describing the amount of hours each employee was scheduled by \'93Day\'94, \'93Night\'94, \'93InShop\'94, and \'93Driver\'94. Should be used to make sure all employees are scheduled properly. If the schedule is for just about any reason inadequate, it can most likely be solved by adjusting TargetHours of employees, saving the file, running the R code again, and reopening the schedule and employeeHours files.\
\

